The paper discusses the need for interpretable and accountable intelligent systems, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The paper also focuses on the evaluation of interpretable machine learning, which is a subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the importance of addressing security and privacy concerns in interpretable machine learning, which falls under the category of cybersecurity (cs.CYBER). Finally, the paper discusses the use of evaluation measures such as precision, recall, and accuracy, which are commonly used in information retrieval (cs.IR).
